block_defaults_desc_list_blocks                                               = \
  Block displays list of %type_names% with various sorting and filtering options. This block is a standard list block \
  with pagination support.

block_defaults_desc_static_filters                                            = \
  [kt|b]Static filters[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  You can filter the displayed list by enabling static filter parameters and specify their filter values directly in\
  block settings.

block_defaults_desc_dynamic_filters                                           = \
  [kt|b]Dynamic filters[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  Dynamic filters allow you to pass filter values in URL, rather than hardcoding them in block settings. However in\
  block settings for each dynamic filter you want to use, you should enable it and specify URL parameter name, that\
  will be used to pass its value in the URL. For example if you want to pass filter value in [kt|b]foo[/kt|b]\
  parameter in the URL, you should make sure that this dynamic filter is enabled and contains [kt|b]foo[/kt|b] value:\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|code]var_filter_xxx = [kt|b]foo[/kt|b][/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  Then in order to enable this filtering, you should pass its filter value in the URL ([kt|b]bar[/kt|b] is the\
  actual value we want to filter in this example):[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]%project_url%/%page_id%.php?[kt|b]foo=bar[/kt|b][/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  In order to hide script and parameter names (e.g. [kt|b]%page_id%.php[/kt|b] and [kt|b]foo[/kt|b]) you may use\
  mod_rewrite rules in your main [kt|b].htaccess[/kt|b] file and have URLs like these:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
    %project_url%/prefix/[kt|b]bar[/kt|b]/[kt|br]\
    %project_url%/prefix/[kt|b]bar[/kt|b].html[kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  If you prefer directory-based URLs, these rewrite rules can be used (the first rule is for pagination and it expects\
  that you have [kt|b]var_from=from[/kt|b] block parameter enabled):[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
    RewriteRule ^prefix/([^/]+)/([0-9]+)/$ %page_id%.php?[kt|b]foo=$1[/kt|b]&from=$2 [L,QSA][kt|br]\
    RewriteRule ^prefix/([^/]+)/$ [kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp]%page_id%.php?[kt|b]foo=$1[/kt|b] [L,QSA][kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  If you prefer file-based URLs, these rewrite rules can be used (the first rule is for pagination and it expects that\
  you have [kt|b]var_from=from[/kt|b] block parameter enabled):[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
    RewriteRule ^prefix/([^/]+)-([0-9]+).html$ %page_id%.php?[kt|b]foo=$1[/kt|b]&from=$2 [L,QSA][kt|br]\
    RewriteRule ^prefix/([^/]+)\u005c.html$ [kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp]%page_id%.php?[kt|b]foo=$1[/kt|b] [L,QSA][kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]


block_defaults_desc_text_search                                               = \
  [kt|b]Search %type_names% by text[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  This block provides support for searching %type_names% by text query. You should enable [kt|b]var_search[/kt|b]\
  block parameter and specify URL parameter name there to allow text search. Also you may need to configure other\
  search-related parameters to adjust search behavior.

block_defaults_desc_related_objects                                           = \
  [kt|b]Related %type_names%[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  You can configure this block to show %type_names% that are similar to some other given %type_names% by using a\
  wide range of criteria. This is so-called 'related' behavior. You should enable [kt|b]mode_related[/kt|b] parameter\
  and additionally you should enable one of the [kt|b]var_%type_single%_xxx[/kt|b] parameters. In order this\
  functionality to start working, either %type_name% ID or %type_name% directory should be passed in URL, so that\
  this block knows which %type_name% it should base from:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
    %project_url%/%page_id%.php?[kt|b]id=123[/kt|b][kt|br]\
    %project_url%/%page_id%.php?[kt|b]dir=%type_single%_directory[/kt|b][kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]

block_defaults_desc_interconnected_objects                                    = \
  [kt|b]Interconnected %type_names%[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  You can configure this block to show %type_names% that are used together with some other categorization objects in\
  content (videos, albums or posts). This is so-called 'interconnected' behavior. For example, for a channel you can\
  display all categories that are used together with this channel in videos. Or for a category you can display all tags\
  that are used in albums together with this category. In order to do that you should enable [kt|b]mode_interconnected[/kt|b]\
  parameter and additionally you should enable one of the [kt|b]var_xxx[/kt|b] parameters located in the same parameter\
  group. In order this functionality to start working, either connected object ID or connected object directory should\
  be passed in URL, so that this block knows which connected object it should base from:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
    %project_url%/%page_id%.php?[kt|b]id=123[/kt|b][kt|br]\
    %project_url%/%page_id%.php?[kt|b]dir=connected_object_directory[/kt|b][kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]

block_defaults_desc_subselects                                                = \
  [kt|b]Selecting additional data for each %type_name%[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  By default list blocks do not select information about connected objects (e.g. connected categories or tags and etc.)\
  so that performance is not affected. If your design requires you to render some additional info for each %type_name% \
  in this list, you should enable parameters that activate additional data selection. You should be aware that \
  selecting additional data may dramatically reduce this block performance. This will not be a problem for blocks that \
  are cached for a long time, but may be a critical performance issue if not cached or used in contexts where caching \
  is not activated.\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  You can find examples of displaying connected data in the following forum article:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]https://forum.kernel-video-sharing.com/topic/28-theme-customization-showing-categories-tags-etc-for-each-video-album-in-list/[kt|br][/kt|code]

block_defaults_desc_list_template                                             = \
  [kt|b]Template code highlights[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  How to display list in template:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
   {{foreach item="[kt|b]item[/kt|b]" from=$data}}[kt|br]\
   [kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp]{{[kt|b]$item[/kt|b].xxx}} {{* <-- use $item variable to access properties of list elements *}}[kt|br]\
   {{/foreach}}[kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  How to check if the list is empty:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
   {{if count($data)==0}}[kt|br]\
   [kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp]the list is empty[kt|br]\
   {{else}}[kt|br]\
   [kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp][kt|sp]the list is not empty[kt|br]\
   {{/if}}[kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]

block_defaults_desc_view_blocks                                               = \
  This block displays data of a single %type_name% (context object) provided via URL parameters.

block_defaults_desc_context_object                                            = \
  [kt|b]Context object[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  In order to specify %type_name% you should either provide its ID and / or its directory in URL parameters configured\
  in [kt|b]var_%type_single%_id[/kt|b] and / or [kt|b]var_%type_single%_dir[/kt|b] block parameters. If both ID and\
  directory are provided in URL, this block will lookup %type_name% by the given ID and will then compare its actual\
  directory value with the one provided in the URL. If they do not match and %type_names% have URL pattern defined in\
  [kt|b]Settings -> Website settings[/kt|b], this block will send HTTP 301 redirect to the correct URL (so-called\
  'document moved' behavior). If you are not using %type_name% IDs to build their page URLs, renaming directory in any\
  %type_name% will lead to HTTP 404 error from its old URL.\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  Blocks of this type are typically put into the very first line of page template, so that site engine queried object\
  data first and then you can display this %type_name% data in site header (title, description and other). In order to\
  do that correctly you should also put block execution result (HTML code generated by this block) into a variable\
  using [kt|b]assign[/kt|b] directive:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]{{insert name="getBlock" block_id="%type_single%_view" block_name="Info" [kt|b]assign="info_result"[/kt|b]}}[/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  This will let you use %type_name% info in the rest of template using this block [kt|b]$storage[/kt|b]:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]\
    {{assign var="page_title" value=[kt|b]$storage.%type_single%_view_info[/kt|b].title}} {{* <-- take page title from %type_name% title *}}[kt|br]\
    {{assign var="page_description" value=[kt|b]$storage.%type_single%_view_info[/kt|b].description}} {{* <-- take page description from %type_name% description *}}[kt|br]\
    ...[kt|br]\
    {{include file="include_header_general.tpl"}} {{* <-- display site header with the set metadata values *}}[kt|br]\
  [/kt|code]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  You can then display block HTML result in any place of template using [kt|b]info_result[/kt|b] variable that you\
  earlier used to assign it to:[kt|br]\
  [kt|code]{{$info_result|smarty:nodefaults}}[/kt|code]







block_defaults_desc_caching_default                                           = \
  [kt|b]Caching[/kt|b]\
  [kt|br]\
  [kt|br]\
  This block can be cached for a long time. The same cache version will be used for all users.


